abstract: LONDON, Nov. 30. -- Mr. Parnell, by telegraph, invited those of his colleagues who were favorable to his retention in the leadership to meet him Saturday evening at the Westminster Palace Hotel. Twenty-four of those invited met Mr. Parnell, and together they discussed the situation. Mr. Parnell informed those present of the relations between himself and the Liberal leaders, and expressed a determination to fight to the last.

abstract: CLEVELAND, Ohio, Nov. 30. -- "I am through with sentiment," said "Al" Johnson to THE TIMES correspondent to-night. "I am not thirty years old yet. My brief experience with baseball has not crippled me financially. I need no sympathy, and deserve none, perhaps, but I'll wager $5,000 that before the League magnates are through with me they'll go down deep into their pockets a good many times.

abstract: Native literature in Bombay appears to be in a flourishing, and is certainly not in a lethargic, condition. It is noted in Mr. Sathe's official report as a curious fact that while so much is heard of the awakening of India to political questions, these publications only include one which relates to politics.

abstract: PROVIDENCE, R.I., Dec. 14. -- Thousands of spectators flocked around the scene of Saturday's half-million-dollar fire to-day. Chief of Police Child ordered the circle of the ropes contracted to within safe distance of the tottering walls in order that the crowds might better survey the ruins. Trains coming into the city and the street-car service brought a multitude of spectators, who came and went till late this evening.

abstract: THE EYES OF DEEP-SEA FISH. -- The queerest thing about deep-sea creatures is their arrangements for vision. Fish that live at very great depths have either no eyes at all or enormously big ones. abstract: SIAMESE GIBBONS. -- I only once saw a specimen of the siamang in captivity at the house of a Malay chief at Sirdang. It was about three feet high, but the stretch of its arms was over five feet. abstract: WINES. -- The vine is, in one respect, out of the many that could be mentioned, a particularly remarkable plant. It might be called a climatometer -- a measurer or indicator of climate. abstract: MOOR BATHS. -- The moor baths, of which much is now heard, and which are provided at many Austrian and German health resorts, were first used at Franzensbad. Some physicians still question their efficacy, while others in Austria and Germany rely upon them to render good service in many maladies.

abstract: The J.W. Dann Manufacturing Company Carriage and Wagon Works, Columbus, Ohio, burned at 6 o'clock yesterday morning. The fire originated in the drying kiln and spread through the building by way of the elevator. It was beyond control when the department arrived. The total damage was $48,000, the estimated value being: Five-story building, $20,000; machinery, $22,000, and stock, $6,000.
